<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Health Care Needs
   Good Business Sense
</HL>
<DATE>
07/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
</IN>
<LP>
   High hospital costs in Kalamazoo are attributed by your
reporter ("Rival Operations -- Competitive Anomaly: Consumers
Pay More in 2-Hospital Towns," page one, June 6) to the
existence of competition between two hospitals, the
implication being that a monopoly would be better. The story,
however, also supports an even more ironic hypothesis -- that
Kalamazoo's large corporate purchasers of hospital services
are responsible for the high costs and their own plight.
   After years of trying to encourage the hospitals to
cooperate rather than compete (probably the cooperation
envisioned would have been unlawful under the antitrust laws
in any event), Kalamazoo's employers are apparently now
considering for the first time purchasing health care just as
they purchase other goods and services -- with price as a
central consideration. Theodore Cooper, M.D., who was quoted
as chairman of Upjohn Co. but who still sounds like the U.S.
assistant secretary of health he once was, admits, "We've
never tried to bid one {hospital} against the other." If
employers had negotiated with the hospitals for particular
services, demanding good quality and a competitive price in
return for their employees' business, the duplication of
services and high prices they complain of would never have
occurred.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Clark C. Havighurst
   Durham, N.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900718-0097
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900718-0097.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Baptist Press's Chiefs Axed
   By News Service's Owners
</HL>
<DATE>
07/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   The top officers of Baptist Press, a prominent religious
news service used by nearly 500 newspapers and magazines
nationwide, were fired by the executive committee of the
Southern Baptist Convention, which owns the service.
   The dismissals of Al Shackleford, 58 years old, director
of the Nashville, Tenn.-based news service, and Dan Martin,
51, its editor, were made effective immediately after the
committee voted in closed session yesterday in Nashville. The
committee named no replacements for the two men, leaving the
43-year-old news service's future unclear.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In June, the committee told the two men to resign by Sept.
30 or they would "be dealt with harshly." They refused. Last
week, the Associated Church Press -- representing 195
Protestant, Catholic and Eastern Orthodox publications --
wrote to Baptist officials urging them to retain Messrs.
Shackleford and Martin.
   Although the committee offered no explanation for its
action, its chairman, Sam Pace of Lawton, Okla., earlier
issued a statement accusing Mr. Shackleford of bias against
fundamentalists, who recently wrested control of the Southern
Baptist Convention from a more moderate faction.
Fundamentalists believe the Bible is literally true in
matters of religion, science and history.
</TEXT>
