<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                         CORPORATE
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Capital Corp. -- $250 million of notes,
due July 24, 2008, is being offered with an 8 1/2% coupon
rate at prices based on prevailing market conditions at the
time of sale to investors. Investors can put their notes in
five years at par. The non-callable notes were priced
initially at par to yield 8.5%, a spread of 0.22 percentage
point above the Treasury's five-year notes. Rated triple-A by
Moody's Investors Service Inc. and Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.,
the issue will be sold through underwriters led by Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets. GECC is the financial arm of General
Electric Co.
   Kaiser Permanente -- $200 million of 9.55% debentures, due
July 15, 2005, was priced at 99.656 to yield 9.593%. The
non-callable debentures were priced at a spread of 1.15
percentage points above the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated
double-A-2 by Moody's and double-A by S&amp;P, the issue will be
sold through underwriters led by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. Kaiser
Permanente is a large prepaid health care delivery system.
   Public Service Electric &amp; Gas Co. -- $125 million of first
mortgage and refunding bonds, due July 1, 2020, was priced at
par to yield 9.75%. The bonds, which are nonrefundable at a
lower interest cost for five years, were won in competitive
bidding by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., who bid 99.626 for a net
cost to the company of 9.787%. Rated single-A-1 by Moody's
and single-A by S&amp;P, the bonds were priced at a spread of
1.30 percentage points above the Treasury's 30-year note. The
bonds were issued by a subsidiary of the Newark, N.J.based
Public Service Enterprise Group Inc.
   Anheuser-Busch Cos. -- $100 million of 8 3/4% notes, due
July 15, 1995, through Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. The company said
the notes will be offered to the public at 99.92% of the face
amount to yield 8.769%. Proceeds will be used for general
corporate purposes, the company said, including repayment of
short-term debt incurred to fund working capital requirements
and the Sea World acquisition that was completed in late
1989. The notes are being issued under a previous shelf
registration that Anheuser-Busch filed with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, the company said.
   Northern Illinois Gas Co. -- $50 million of first mortgage
notes, due July 15, 1995, was priced with a coupon of 8.70%
at 99.896 to yield 8.725%. The issue was won in competitive
bidding by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets, which offered a
price of 99.546 for a net interest cost to the company of
8.814%. The notes, which are non-callable for four years,
were priced at a spread of 0.42 percentage point above the
Treasury's five-year note. The issue was rated double-A-1 by
Moody's and double-A by S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNICIPAL
                                                                                                       

   Connecticut -- $325 million of general obligation bonds,
due July 15, 1991-2010, excluding 1994, 1999 and 2002, were
tentatively priced by a Merrill Lynch Capital Markets group
to yield from 5.80% in 1991 to 6.95% in 2007-2010. There are
no term bonds. The bonds are rated double-A by Moody's and
S&amp;P.
   New York State -- $225 million of various purpose general
obligation bonds, due July 15, 1991-2020, apparently were won
by a First Boston Corp. group with a bid setting the true
interest cost at 6.807%. The bonds, rated single-A by Moody's
and S&amp;P, were priced for reoffering to yield from 6.00% in
1992 to 7.15% in 2009-2020. Bonds due in 1991 aren't formally
reoffered.
   San Francisco Bay Area Rapid Transit -- $159 million of
sales tax revenue refunding bonds, Series 1990, due July 1,
1992-2004, 2009, 2010 and 2011, with capital appreciation
bonds due 2001-2004, were priced by a Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co. group. The bonds are priced to yield from 5.90%
in 1992 to 7.04% in 2009. Current interest serial bonds are
priced at par to yield from 5.90% in 1992 to 6.70% in 2000.
There are $56 million of 6 3/4% term bonds priced at 97 to
yield 7.04% in 2009. There are $13.9 million of 6 3/4% term
bonds priced at 98 to yield 6.94% in 2010. There are $14.9
million of 6 3/4% term bonds priced at 97.95 to yield 6.94%
in 2011. Bonds due in 2010 and 2011 are non-callable. Capital
appreciation bonds are priced to yield to maturity from 6.65%
in 2001 to 6.75% in 2003 and 2004. The bonds are rated
single-A-1 by Moody's and single-A-plus by S&amp;P, excluding
bonds due in 2009-2011 and capital appreciation bonds due in
20012004, which are insured and rated triple-A by Moody's and
S&amp;P.
   West Virginia School Building Authority -- $102.9 million
of capital improvement revenue bonds, Series 1990 B, due July
1, 1991-2007, 2010, 2017 and 2020, were tentatively priced by
a Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. group to
yield from 5.90% in 1991 to 7.22% in 2017. Current interest
serial bonds are priced to yield from 5.90% in 1991 to 7.05%
in 2003. Bonds due in 2004-2007 aren't formally reoffered.
There are $11.1 million of 6.75% term bonds priced at 95.50
to yield 7.18% in 2010. There are $36.3 million of 6.75% term
bonds priced at 94.50 to yield 7.22% in 2017. There are $21.2
million of 6% term bonds priced at 86.25 to yield 7.11% in
2020. The bonds are insured and rated triple-A by Moody's and
S&amp;P.
   Michigan State Hospital Authority -- $101 million of
hospital revenue bonds, Oakwood Hospital Obligated Group
issue, Series 1990 A, due July 1, 1992-2002, 2010 and 2018
were tentatively priced by a Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. group to
yield from 6.10% in 1992 to 7.18% in 2018. Current interest
serial bonds are priced at par to yield from 6.10% in 1992 to
7.00% in 2002. There are $29 million of 7% term bonds priced
at 99.00 to yield 7.09% in 2010. There are $50.5 million of
7.10% term bonds priced at 99.00 to yield 7.18% in 2018. The
bonds are insured and rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Maryland Health and Higher Education Facilities Authority
-- $89.5 million of revenue bonds, Francis Scott Key Medical
