<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   GULF STATES UTILITIES CO. -- Moody's Investors Service
Inc. said it raised the ratings on about $2.4 billion of
senior debt of this Beaumont, Texas-based utility. In making
the upgrade, the ratings concern cited the recent settlement
of a four year-old legal dispute related to power purchases
from Southern Co., Georgia. Moody's raised the ratings on
GSU's first-mortgage bonds and secured pollution control
revenue bonds to Ba-2 from Ba-3, and raised the unsecured
pollution control revenue bonds, Eurodebentures and
convertible debentures to Ba-3 from single-B-1. Ratings on
the utility's preferred and preference stock were confirmed
at Caa.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   THREE NEW JERSEY BANKS saw their credit ratings cut by
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., which cited loan portfolios weakened
by the slump in the real estate market. The rating on the
preferred stock of UJB Financial Corp., Princeton, fell to
triple-B-minus from triple-B; the subordinated debt of
Central Jersey Bancorp, Freehold, dropped to double-B-plus
from triple-B; and the senior debt of Summit Bancorp, Summit,
dropped to triple- B-plus from single-A. Overall, the
downgrades by the New York credit-rating company affect
securities valued at $30 million at UJB, $22 million at
Central Jersey, and $157 million at Summit.
</TEXT>
