<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Tidying the Revolution
</HL>
<DATE>
07/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN EUROP FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   World leaders are coming to resemble those sanitation
workers who come in and sweep up after a parade. The people
make a dramatic gesture, and then the leaders come in a few
months later to make everything tidy.
   When the German people streamed through the Berlin Wall,
they effectively declared Germany a single sovereign nation,
able to choose its own alliances. Thus, not long after the
wall came down, it was clear that Germany would remain in
NATO. The diplomacy of the past several months merely gussied
up that certainty. The final touch came Monday when Mikhail
Gorbachev finally agreed to pull the 350,000 Soviet troops
out of East Germany within the next three or four years so
that a united Germany could have "full and unrestricted
sovereignty."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The diplomacy has been conducted competently. The Soviets
first tried to play on aroused European fears about renewed
German hegemony, with Foreign Minister Shevardnadze's bizarre
suggestion that there be an international referendum on
German reunification. Then the Soviets played on left-wing
idealism, suggesting that Germany should join both NATO and
the Warsaw Pact as part of one happy family of nations. The
Soviets also appealed to technocratic gradualists, saying
Germany could be part of NATO politically, but not
militarily. Then they suggested that Germans reunify slowly
under the supervision of the victorious World War II powers.
   It must have then been clear to the Soviets that their
wild proposals were going nowhere. Mr. Gorbachev must have
realized that even though he could do nothing to prevent
Germany from staying in NATO, he could nonetheless charge a
fee for acknowledging the arrangement. So he entered into
negotiations to settle on a price, which has now been met,
but not made public. Mr. Gorbachev reportedly told Premier
Mitterrand, "the same day the reunification of Germany is
announced, a general will be sitting in my armchair." But
that was wind. Mr. Gorbachev still has his seat.
   On the Western side, the patient handling of the issue
serves as a model of Western diplomatic cooperation. At the
Houston Summit, the leaders, under the influence of Prime
Minister Thatcher, arrived at a compromise whereby the G-7
powers would not give joint aid to the Soviets, but
individual nations could. The unspoken message was that aid
will not help the still-unreformed Soviet economy, but is
worthwhile if it will seal Germany's membership in the
alliance. The London NATO summit sent the proper military
signals, and to climax the deal, Chancellor Kohl flew to
Zheleznovodsk with his checkbook.
   The German-Soviet agreement brings NATO up to date. There
is no need to find a replacement for NATO through distended
disarmament talks. Instead, the Western powers can now focus
on issues that were swept under the rug in order to strike
this deal. The West forsook independence movements in the
breakaway republics so as not to ruin negotiations on
Germany. Now that the West's house is in order there is no
need to ignore the yearnings of the Soviet peoples. The U.S.
decision to meet with members of the Russian democratic
opposition party is an important step in the right direction.
   Western leaders need not worry about having a vision for
the future. The people will lead the parade. The leaders need
only follow and formalize.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900718-0084
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900718-0084.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Industry Output
   Increased 0.4%
   During June
   ---
   Utilities' Production Led
   Rise Due to Heat Wave;
   Capacity Use Up a Bit
   ----
   By Hilary Stout
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The nation's industrial production rose
modestly last month, bolstered by a jump in utility output
during a torrid late-June heat wave, the Federal Reserve
reported.
   Industrial output grew 0.4% in June following a 0.6%
increase in May. With the rise in production, the country's
factories, utilities and mines used more of their capacity in
June: 83.5%, up from 83.3% in May.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The modest growth in output was higher than many analysts
expected, but it still left economists disagreeing over the
state of U.S. industrial health.
   The 2.1% leap in utility output, largely due to a surge in
air conditioner use, was obviously temporary. And another big
factor, a substantial increase in automobile production,
probably won't continue either, several analysts predicted.
Car companies have been fattening inventories in anticipation
of contract talks with the United Auto Workers union, which
get under way today.
   "This is actually confirmation, if we needed any at this
juncture, that the economy is running low and slow and
probably will continue to do so because the increases in
industrial production and capacity utilization are related to
factors that are temporary, not fundamental," said David
Littmann, senior economist at Manufacturers National Bank of
Detroit.
   But while auto and utility production accounted for
three-fourths of the total increase in output, according to
the Fed, a number of other categories also posted small
gains. Production of paper, chemicals, appliances, television
sets, fuels, furniture and business equipment all rose.
   "I'm encouraged," said Stephen Roach, senior economist at
Morgan Stanley in New York. "I think these data do reflect a
gathering of momentum in the manufacturing sector. I think
that could be an important swing factor to an improved tone
in the U.S. economy."
   U.S. manufacturing, hurt by the Fed's efforts to fight
inflation by keeping interest rates high, has been ailing for
more than a year. Just a few weeks ago, the Labor Department
reported that factory employment continued to decline in
June, the 14th month of the past 15 in which it has dropped.
   But Mr. Roach said the decrease doesn't entirely reflect
weakness. "I think the job cuts are largely restructuring
driven by a manufacturing sector that wants to compete in the
global economy." He cited recent strong productivity gains in
manufacturing as one reason behind continued improvement in
output.
   "We're still looking at a manufacturing sector that
overall is in transition to leaner, meaner stuff," Mr.
Littmann said.
   Recent government reports have suggested to some analysts
that the worst may be past for many manufacturing industries.
Factory orders grew substantially in May. Exports continue to
improve, the Commerce Department reported yesterday.
Moreover, the Fed last week eased its grip on credit for the
first time since December, allowing a pivotal interest rate
to fall slightly.
   Still, most analysts expect continued improvement in
manufacturing to be gradual.
   Figures in the industrial production and capacity reports
are seasonally adjusted.
                                                                                                       

   Here is a summary of the Federal Reserve Board's report on
industrial production in June. The figures are seasonally
adjusted.
                                                                                                       

                                        % change from
                                       May         June
                                      1990         1989
                                                                                                       

   Total ...........................   0.4          1.2
     Consumer goods ................   0.7          1.8
     Business equipment ............   0.9          2.6
     Defense and space ............. - 0.1        - 1.0
   Manufacturing only ..............   0.5          1.3
     Durable goods .................   0.5          1.1
     Nondurable goods ..............   0.4          1.6
                                                                                                       

   Mining .......................... - 1.5          0.6
                                                                                                       

   Utilities .......................   2.1          2.7
                                                                                                       

   The industrial production index for June stood at 109.8%
of the 1987 average.
</TEXT>
