<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   RJR Nabisco's Junk Surges Again, but Activity
   Is Thin Ahead of Today's June Inflation Data
   ----
   By Tom Herman and Robert Sherman
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   RJR SLCTC EUROP FLE FRE FNM
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Prices surged on RJR Nabisco Inc. junk bonds
for the second day in a row, but most other bond prices and
interest rates were little changed.
   RJR Nabisco's bonds are surging in popularity because of a
huge $6.9 billion refinancing plan announced Sunday by
company officials. The plan is designed to ease the food and
tobacco company's enormous debt burdens and strengthen its
financial backbone.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   RJR's largest issue, which soared more than eight points
Monday, added another 2 3/8 points yesterday to close at 94
1/8. Investor enthusiasm about the RJR news spilled over into
other sectors of the junk bond market, helping to lift prices
of some issues by about half a point, or $5 for each $1,000
face amount.
   But while trading volume in RJR bonds was heavy, volume
elsewhere in the junk-bond market generally was "very light,"
said Joseph Bencivenga, head of high-yield bond research at
Salomon Brothers Inc. Trading generally "was so thin that I
find it hard to describe what happened to the market as a
whole as much of a rally, aside from RJR where we saw a lot
of activity," he said."
   Elsewhere in the credit markets, Treasury bond prices held
steady for the second day in a row. Yields on 30-year
Treasury bonds continued to hover about 8.45%. Rates on
short-term Treasury bills also were flat.
   Treasury-bond trading was sluggish all day as investors
awaited a government report this morning on consumer prices
in June. Also this morning, Federal Reserve Board Chairman
Alan Greenspan will present the central bank's semiannual
economic and monetary report at a Senate Banking Committee
hearing.
   In addition, traders are waiting for signs that the
government will take steps to slash its huge budget deficit.
If the government shrinks the deficit, that would reduce
borrowing pressures in the credit markets. And a large
deficit-cutting package might persuade the Fed to reduce
short-term interest rates further.
   "My impression is that people are expecting at least a $50
billion to $55 billion cut in the budget deficit," said
Morgan Stark, president and chief executive of Chemical
Securities Inc. "The market will be very disappointed if this
isn't done, and if it isn't done in a timely, credible
fashion."
   This morning's inflation report is expected to show a
moderate rise in consumer prices of 0.3% for June, according
to a survey of 21 economists by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report. That would follow increases of 0.2% in both May and
April. Excluding the food and energy components, an increase
of 0.4% is expected, analysts say.
   Inflation fears that haunted the markets early this year
now appear to be fading rapidly, with investors focusing
increasingly on growing signs of economic weakness. "We
definitely prefer bonds over stocks," says Arthur A.
Micheletti, vice president at Bailard Biehl &amp; Kaiser, a San
Mateo, Calif., firm that manages about $1.3 billion for both
individuals and institutions.
   "It's a coin's toss whether the economy already is in a
recession or merely heading for slow growth," Mr. Micheletti
said. Either scenario "would mean strong gains" for holders
of U.S. Treasury bonds, while the stock market is "an
accident waiting to happen."
   Bailard Biehl has about half its individual clients' funds
in bonds, nearly all of which are in U.S. Treasury issues.
"This isn't the time to reach for yield" and buy lower-rated
bonds, he said. "This is a time to go for safety and
liquidity."
                                                                                                       

   Junk, Corporate Issues
                                                                                                       

   RJR Nabisco's surging junk bonds dominated activity in the
corporate-bond arena again yesterday.
   RJR's pay-in-kind bonds posted especially large gains. The
company's 17% exchangeable pay-in-kind debentures maturing in
2007 climbed 2 3/8 points to 94 1/8 on the New York Stock
Exchange. And its 17 3/8% convertible pay-in-kind debentures
due in 2009 rose 1 1/2 points to 115 7/8. Pay-in-kind bonds
pay interest in the form of additional securities.
   Trading volume was very heavy. Southland Corp.'s junk
bonds also posted solid gains as investors reacted with
relief to the company's announcement Monday that it had
agreed in principle on a restructuring proposal with a
bondholders' steering committee and a group of Japanese
investors.
   That agreement averted a possible bankruptcy-law filing
and drove up prices yesterday of some Southland issues by 1/2
point to one point. The agreement differs significantly from
a previous debt-exchange offer from the company.
   Southland, the troubled parent company of the 7-Eleven
retail convenience stores, previously had said it didn't
intend to make a June 15 interest payment on its senior
subordinated debt. That payment officially went into default
Sunday. Without an agreement from senior debtholders, the
company could have been driven into bankruptcy proceedings.
   Separately, prices of investment-grade corporate bonds
were little changed on the day. Activity in the new-issue
investment-grade market has perked up lately, and several
bond specialists expect that to continue. "I think you're
going to continue to see more {investment-grade} corporate
supply" soon, said Thomas Pura, a partner at Goldman, Sachs &amp;
Co.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   British government bond prices tumbled, erasing all of
Monday's gains, after the government reported an unexpectedly
large budget deficit for June.
   Among actively traded issues, Britain's 11.75% bonds due
2003/2007 fell 3/4 point to 102 7/32 to yield 11.41%.
Britain's 12% bonds due 1995 declined 7/32 point to 99 3/4 to
yield 12.08%.
   U.K. bonds, known as gilts, have been star performers in
the international bond markets during the past few months.
Several analysts expect the rally to continue this summer
because of growing signs of weakness in the U.K.'s economy
that could drive down interest rates, which move in the
opposite direction from bond prices. But yesterday's budget
deficit news brought the recent rally to an abrupt halt.
   Britain's budget deficit totaled #2.6 billion ($4.69
billion) in June. That was sharply higher than analysts'
estimates of #1 billion to #1.5 billion. The bulging deficit
raises the possibility that the government will have to
resume selling sizable amounts of new gilts later this fiscal
year to meet its funding needs, economists said.
   Separately, West German government bond prices slumped,
following the lead of futures prices. Several traders said
they had expected a temporary setback following the market's
week-long surge. Bonn's 8.75% bonds, due 2000, fell 0.35
point to 101.60 to yield 8.65%. Japanese bond prices also
fell, hurt by high short-term interest rates.
   A Salomon Brothers Inc. report released in New York
yesterday predicted that inflation-adjusted yields on U.S.
government bonds will remain considerably lower than those of
major European countries through 1991.
   Inflation-adjusted yields on U.S. government bonds now are
about 4%, said Nicholas Sargen, a director of bond market
research at Salomon. That, he said, is more than two
percentage points less than those on bonds of Germany,
France, Netherlands, and Canada. U.K. bonds have a real yield
of about 5% to 5.5%, according to the report by Messrs.
Sargen and John Lipsky of Salomon.
   The report cited "heightened competition for funds in
Europe and increased uncertainty about financing requirements
for Germany and Eastern Europe" as the most important
considerations in keeping real European bond yields high.
                                                                                                       

   Municipal Bonds
                                                                                                       

   A large volume of new municipal bond issues hit the market
yesterday.
   For example, New York sold $225 million of bonds through
competitive bidding. The winning bid came from a group of
underwriters led by First Boston Corp. The underwriters then
reoffered the bonds to investors at prices to yield from 6%
in 1992 to 7.15% in 2009-2020.
   First Boston officials said the unsold balance among
underwriters was about $72 million. The bonds are rated
single-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Investor demand for New York tax-free bonds typically is
strong among New Yorkers because of the state's very high
income tax rate. Moreover, New York City imposes a steep
income tax, too, and many voters fear Gotham taxes have
nowhere to go but up.
   Connecticut offered $325 million of general obligation
bonds. The issue was tentatively priced by underwriters, led
by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets, to yield from 5.80% on
bonds due in 1991 to 6.95% in 20072010. The bonds are rated
double-A by both Moody's Investors Service Inc. and Standard
&amp; Poor's Inc.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   Treasury-bond prices were little changed again yesterday
as traders marked time ahead of today's economic news.
   Among active issues, the Treasury's 30-year bonds were
quoted late in the day at 103 1/8, to yield 8.45%, unchanged
from the previous day.
   "It was a very quiet, low volume session with minimal
price change," said William Sullivan, director of money
market research at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage, Asset-backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage securities prices ended unchanged to slightly
firmer, after spending the session in stifling trading
ranges.
   Only one major offering has been priced so far this week
-- a $122 million Fleetwood Credit Corp. issue backed by
loans for recreational vehicles that was priced yesterday by
First Boston Corp. as 9% securities at 99 18/32 to yield
9.204%.
   Fleetwood Credit is a unit of Fleetwood Enterprises Inc.,
Riverside, Calif., whose products include travel trailers and
motor homes.
   Among active secondary issues for August delivery,
Government National Mortgage Association 9.5% securities were
up 3/ 32 at 99 26/32, Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. 9.5%
issues were up 2/32 at 99 1/8 and Federal National Mortgage
Association 9.5% issues were up 2/32 at 99 5/8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900718-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900718-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Neil Bush, Despite Applying `Smith Smell Test,'
   Gets Compared With Billy Carter, Donald Nixon
   ----
   By Timothy Noah
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   F
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BIOGRAPHY (BIO)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   DENVER -- Neil Bush calls it the Smith Smell Test.
   "People call up and say, `Hey Neil, I've got this great
deal,'" says the president's embattled but still amiable son.
"The smell test is: If my name were Neil Smith, would they be
asking me to engage in this venture with them?"
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Bush says he's never violated his smell test by
trading on being George Bush's son. But with the spotlight on
his role in the collapse of Silverado Banking, Savings &amp; Loan
Association, which is expected to cost taxpayers $1 billion,
comparisons inevitably are made with Billy Carter, Donald
Nixon and other presidential relatives whose finances brought
embarrassment to the White House. As a former Silverado
director, Mr. Bush has come under fire for overseeing loans
that involved two investors in his oil company.
   But what has caught public attention is a $100,000 loan
that Mr. Bush received before joining the Silverado board
from Kenneth Good, a Denver real-estate developer and
investor in JNB Exploration, Mr. Bush's oil company. Mr. Good
arranged to invest the money in the commodities market on Mr.
Bush's behalf, with the understanding that any profits would
be Mr. Bush's, while any losses would be absorbed by Mr.
Good.
   Mr. Bush, who not only looks but also acts like the Jimmy
Stewart of "Mr. Smith Goes to Washington," made headlines by
conceding in congressional testimony that the Good loan
sounded "a little fishy."
   Mr. Bush's friends say he lacks a sophisticated
understanding of the darker forces in life. "I think there's
a refreshing naivete about Neil," says Mr. Bush's adviser,
former Democratic Rep. Thomas Ashley, who's known George Bush
since his Skull and Bones days at Yale. "He's not jaded."
   Since Neil Bush's youth, when he was afflicted with
dyslexia -- his brother Marvin recalls that "homework would
take him a little bit longer" than the other Bush children --
he has been known for his good-natured willingness to pitch
into any task. While his siblings would scatter when their
parents ordered that yard work be done, recalls Marvin Bush,
"Neil would step up and say, `Yeah, great.'"
   Friends and business associates agree that Neil Bush's
family name lent him a certain aura within the Denver
business community when he settled there after working on his
father's 1980 presidential bid. Mr. Bush put in two years at
Amoco Corp. to learn the oil business, then left that
$30,000-a-year job to start an oil-exploration company of his
own. Investors were drawn to Mr. Bush "partly, I suppose,
because he was the son of the vice president," concedes Evans
Nash, Neil Bush's former partner. "I'm sure that helped him
meet people."
   Even Mr. Bush's lawyer concedes that being George Bush's
son raised Neil's profile in Denver. "We don't have a lot of
celebrities," explains attorney James Nesland. "We had Marvin
Davis for a while. Now he's gone," he says, registering that
oil man's departure for Hollywood with a shrug.
   Settled in Denver, Neil Bush became a fixture on the local
political scene, giving speeches at Lincoln Day dinners and
stumping for his father and a variety of local Republican
candidates. "He's an enthusiastic speaker," notes Bruce
Benson, chairman of the Colorado Republican Party. "He speaks
of good Republican values."
   Neil Bush can be startlingly blunt in enunciating
conservative themes. According to one local news account, Mr.
Bush told a group of Hispanic voters in 1988 that welfare was
"worse than slavery."
   Mr. Bush also settled into Denver's social elite. With his
wife, Sharon, and three children, he lived in suburban
seclusion amid rolling greens and humming golf carts inside a
walled country-club development. The handsome young couple
became a fixture at dinner parties and charity events.
   It was at one such party in 1985 that Neil Bush met
Michael Wise, chairman of Silverado. Mr. Wise was seeking a
new director for Silverado's board -- preferably someone
young, because the board was top-heavy with older members,
and preferably someone with experience in the oil business,
which was underrepresented. Mr. Bush accepted. "I considered
it a chance to learn," he later told the Denver Post.
   With no experience in banking, Mr. Bush, then 30 years
old, nevertheless seemed a logical choice to those close to
Mr. Wise. "Mike Wise seemed to like to be a first-class
dresser," observes Alexander Walter, a former loan-portfolio
manager at Silverado. "His automobile was always impeccably
clean." Neil Bush, Mr. Walter implies, was another such
ornament.
   Mr. Wise declined to return calls, and through an
intermediary referred all inquiries to his lawyer, Bettina
Lawton. Ms. Lawton says Mr. Bush's last name was "certainly
not a primary consideration" when Mr. Wise chose him for the
board.
   Despite Mr. Bush's youth and inexperience in banking
matters, former Silverado officials say Mr. Bush was no less
able a board member than the others. According to Mr. Walter,
most had "no hands-on experience" with the complex
Silverado's business. Former Silverado board member Diane
Ingels says Mr. Bush was a "very diligent" director who "met
with other directors and with management to enhance his
understanding."
   Still, Mr. Bush remains defensive about his qualifications
to sit on Silverado's board. Sitting in his office
overlooking downtown Denver, a small bust of his father
behind him, he lurches unprompted from discussing his work on
a political campaign into a defense of his work on
Silverado's board. "I was just as well prepared to be on that
board as anyone," he protests.
   Mr. Bush is also emphatic in denying that Mr. Good's
risk-free loan violated the Smith Smell Test. "It's just his
way of having fun," Mr. Bush says. "I wasn't going to deny
him his chance of having fun."
   Mr. Bush says Mr. Good set up similar accounts for Mr.
Good's secretary and bookkeeper. Mr. Good couldn't be reached
for comment, but in testimony last month before the House
Banking Committee, he described the loans as "a means of
attracting and keeping loyal business associates." Still,
neither of Mr. Bush's two partners at JNB Exploration
received such loans. Mr. Bush says they weren't as close to
Mr. Good. The money was eventually lost when the commodities
investments went sour.
   Meanwhile, Mr. Bush is wrestling against
conflict-of-interest charges by the federal Office of Thrift
Supervision concerning his service on the Silverado board.
The thrift office has charged that as a Silverado director
Mr. Bush voted on loans to William Walters, a Denver real
estate agent who was one of two original investors in JNB
Exploration. Mr. Bush answers that there wasn't any legal
requirement that he abstain from the votes.
   The thrift office also contends that Mr. Bush failed to
properly disclose his interest when he helped Mr. Good
receive a $900,000 line of credit from Silverado in order to
assist an Argentine project involving JNB Exploration. But
Mr. Bush produced a memo that appears to demonstrate that his
interest was disclosed to the board before it approved the
line of credit. These and other charges will be publicly
aired at administrative hearings to be held this September in
Denver.
   Amid everything, Mr. Bush maintains a self-deprecating
wit. He has "no airs or graces about him," observes
Republican political consultant Peter Teeley, who recently
phoned Mr. Bush to offer advice and support. Mr. Nesland, the
lawyer, says that after he scolded Mr. Bush for his "fishy"
gaffe, Mr. Bush clipped a newspaper photograph of himself at
the hearing, with Mr. Nesland and Sharon Bush sitting behind
him. "I can't believe he said that," Mr. Bush scribbled in a
bubble drawn above Mr. Nesland's head, according to Mr.
Nesland. "Oh no, not again," Mr. Bush wrote in another bubble
above his wife.
   Indeed, Mr. Bush's spirits are sufficiently buoyant that,
in the midst of seeing himself portrayed as a major S&amp;L
villain, he can still envision pursuing a career in politics.
Ten years from now, he muses, "I may be a U.S. senator. Who
knows?"
</TEXT>
