<HL>
   Financial Concerns
   Report Higher Profit
   For Second Quarter
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
07/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   GWF GDW
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<LP>
   Great Western Financial Corp. and Golden West Financial
Corp. reported higher second-quarter earnings, citing growth
in home loans despite predictions of a decline in the
California real estate market.
   Great Western said net income was $78.2 million, or 60
cents a share, up 51% from $51.9 million, or 40 cents a
share, a year earlier. The Beverly Hills, Calif., bank
holding company said return on assets equaled 0.82% of
assets, up from 0.58% a year earlier. Total new loans in the
quarter were $3.6 billion, compared with $3.4 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, Oakland, Calif.-based Golden West said net in
the same period was up 22% to a record $49 million, or 78
cents a share, from $40 million, or 64 cents a share. Its
return equaled 0.95% of assets, up from 0.86%.
